132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1074
H.P. 696 House of Representatives, March 18, 2025
An Act to Remove the Limit on the Length of Probation That May
Be Served for Aggravated Attempted Murder
Received by the Clerk of the House on March 14, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Criminal Justice and Public Safety pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed pursuant to
Joint Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative LAJOIE of Lewiston.
Cosponsored by Senator CYRWAY of Kennebec and
Representatives: ARDELL of Monticello, BRIDGEO of Augusta, DILL of Old Town,
MALON of Biddeford, NUTTING of Oakland, PERKINS of Dover-Foxcroft, ROLLINS of
Augusta.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 17-A MRSA §1804, sub-§1, as enacted by PL 2019, c. 113, Pt. A, §2, is
3 amended to read:
4 1. Limit on length of probation. Except as provided in subsections 2, 3, 4, 4-A, 5
5 and 6, the period of probation for a person may not exceed:
6 A. For a Class A crime, 4 years;
7 B. For a Class B crime, 3 years;
8 C. For a Class C crime, 2 years; and
9 D. For a Class D or Class E crime, one year.
10 Sec. 2. 17-A MRSA §1804, sub-§4-A is enacted to read:
11 4-A. Exception to limits when person sentenced for aggravated attempted
12 murder. The period of probation for a person sentenced for aggravated attempted murder
13 pursuant to section 152-A, subsection 2 is any term of years.
14 SUMMARY
1155 This bill amends the Maine Criminal Code to provide that the period of probation for
1166 a person sentenced for aggravated attempted murder is any term of years.
